Assignment 7: Upwelling Visualization¶

Now that we've run the ROMS Upwelling case, we want to look at the output.¶

Additional details about the Upwelling case can be found at: https://www.myroms.org/wiki/UPWELLING_CASE¶

Let's get started!¶

xi_rho_index = 0  # Goes from 0 to 42
time_index = 0    # Goes from 0 to 20

# Create the figure with a 2x3 grid layout
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15.0, 10.0))

# Define each variable and its properties, including the appropriate dimensions for slicing
variables = {
    'temp': {'name': 'temperature', 'units': 'Celsius', 'cmap': cmo.thermal, 'ax': fig.add_subplot(2, 3, 1), 'isel': {'xi_rho': xi_rho_index, 'ocean_time': time_index}},
    'salt': {'name': 'salinity', 'units': 'PSU', 'cmap': cmo.haline, 'ax': fig.add_subplot(2, 3, 2), 'isel': {'xi_rho': xi_rho_index, 'ocean_time': time_index}},
    'u': {'name': 'u-velocity', 'units': 'm/s', 'cmap': cmo.balance, 'ax': fig.add_subplot(2, 3, 3), 'isel': {'xi_u': xi_rho_index, 'ocean_time': time_index}},
    'v': {'name': 'v-velocity', 'units': 'm/s', 'cmap': cmo.balance, 'ax': fig.add_subplot(2, 3, 4), 'isel': {'xi_rho': xi_rho_index, 'ocean_time': time_index}},
    'w': {'name': 'vertical velocity', 'units': 'm/s', 'cmap': cmo.speed, 'ax': fig.add_subplot(2, 3, 5), 'isel': {'xi_rho': xi_rho_index, 'ocean_time': time_index}}
}

# Loop through each variable to plot in its designated subplot
for var, props in variables.items():
    # Select the data with appropriate slicing
    data = his[var].isel(**props['isel'])
    
    # Determine the x and y coordinates based on the variable's available dimensions
    x_coord = 'eta_rho' if 'eta_rho' in data.dims else 'eta_v' if 'eta_v' in data.dims else None
    y_coord = 's_rho' if 's_rho' in data.dims else 's_w' if 's_w' in data.dims else None
    
    # Only plot if we have valid x and y coordinates
    if x_coord and y_coord:
        # Plot with contourf in the appropriate subplot
        c = props['ax'].contourf(data[x_coord], data[y_coord], data, cmap=props['cmap'])
        fig.colorbar(c, ax=props['ax'], label=f"{props['name']} ({props['units']})")
        
        # Set labels and title for each subplot
        props['ax'].set_xlabel(x_coord)
        props['ax'].set_ylabel('depth of RHO-points [m]')
        props['ax'].set_title(f"{props['name']} at xi_rho = {xi_rho_index}")
        
       

# Adjust layout to prevent overlapping of subplots
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#7. What differences do you see when you look at the output in the average, diagnostic, and restart file? What purposes do these 4 output files serve and why do they differ?¶

Average= averages over longer time scales, allows for a broader view with smoother images from data. Diagnostic: derived variables used for additional modeling. Restart: contains peramiters for variables allowing to restart models. 3 of the files offers a different data set to work with and can produce models of varying resolutions. Some can be used to give truth to other models.
